(6/6) Typologies provide a means to identify coastal wetland sites that share similar characteristics & distinguish these sites from others (at a broad spatial scale). This new research doesn't aim to reflect conservation priorities, but can still inform important conservation🌎

(5/6) We use the 18 typology scenario to describe regional case studies. Here we show west coast Canada and Papua New Guinea, along with the relevant diagnostic indicators for their respective typologies. https://t.co/HRouql5bkc

(4/6) For the 5-typology scenario, sites are characterised by:
29% 👉 high land & marine-based impacts, with a high proportion of threatened species
13% 👉 high climate-based impacts
9% 👉 refuges with lower impacts, high fish density & lower proportion of threatened species https://t.co/5GPF8JhUmF

(3/6) After accounting for #environmental covariates and gap-filling missing data, we obtained 2 levels of clustering at 5 & 18 typologies.

 These 2 levels provide outputs at different scales that can be used in different ways.

(2/6) We analysed 34 indicators relating to:
➡️habitat extent change
➡️ecological structure & function
➡️cumulative impacts to coastal wetlands.

Using indicator correlations, we identified spatially-explicit ‘typologies’ that characterise clusters of sites with similar status.

(1/6) 📣Our new paper explained in 6 tweets!

We set out to combine existing #ecosystem #indicators of 🌿#mangroves 🌱#seagrass & #saltmarsh to gain a more holistic understanding of the general status of coastal ecosystems around the world🌏

https://t.co/kXM43Q4rnu

Thanks to our authors @SieversSci @bluecology @ChristinABuelow @WorldInPlainEng @turschwell @fern_adame @oceangriffiths @HolgateBriana @tomonlocation @vivtulloch M.R. Chowdhury, 
P. Ermgassen, S. Lee, A. Lillebo, B. Mackey, P. Maxwell, A. Rajkaran, @anaifsousa @ConnollyLab

Conservation relies on ecosystem indicators to track progress - studying interrelationships between 34 indicators for #mangroves, #seagrass & #saltmarsh, we simplify the global mosaic of coastal wetland status.  
New study lead by @SieversSci @GriffithARI
